text: For those of you wondering why they call this movie, Green Book...  The Green book was an old business directory - kind of like the yellow pages. Except it was a list of businesses that would accept blacks as patrons. Hotels, gas stations, restaurants, etcetera. Blacks used to travel with the Green Book whenever they went on long road trips. It was essential.

text: Is this going to be a good movie? Yes.  Is the general public still being brainwashed into believing that racism is still real? Yes. (Are there people who are outwardly racist? Sure. Maybe 1 in 1000. But that's probably the same proportion of murderer, thief, or rapist. Bad, yes. But not some national crisis. Don't believe it? See the #WalkAway movement and footage of Trump rallies. Salt n pepper.)  If you think "this movie is what the country needs right now", you are drinking the propaganda koolaid. Although the overall message will be something like "we're all the same on the inside", the REALITY is you will be exposed to ALL the scenes in the film that remind you of racism. And after the movie makes a big debut, there will be talk shows and radio spots with activists saying things like, "this is a reminder that racism is real and we need to be have a discussion about it...." Remember, slavery was abolished and rights for blacks was won. Why are we still going on about it?  Imagine when slavery was abolished and a slave owner opened his gates. But one slave stays in the field and says, "I want to stay here to be content reminded about how bad it was."  Get the slavery out of your head, go make a friend of another ethnicity, stop ripping the bandage off a fresh wound and crying that it still hurts.

text: Loved this movie - really great!  I loved how the black man was trying to get the white man to take more advantage of what he could be and have, that he was missing opportunities.  Not that he was gong to change him.  But I think about black people today walking, talking and acting in a stereotypical "black" manner.    That stereotype didn't exist before the late 60's early 70's (watch the TV show Goodtimes about a black family - the mother, father, daughter and youngest son all acted and talked like Americans.  The older son "JJ" had the "black" affection.  It never really existed before then, and has remained since then.  John Amos, the father character demanded they change it as it was demeaning to black people, they refused, and he left the show).    I think those who choose to engage as such are limiting their opportunities to break into better paying jobs, just as Tony wasn't about to get a white collar job by walking, talking and acting like a goomba.  Opportunities exist for all people to make something better of themselves regardless of color, race, gender, etc.  But you have to choose it.  One thing that helps to move up beyond kitchen/restaurant/janatorial/barrister, etc work., is don't put tattoos all over you skin that are visible in work clothes.  If executives don't do it/have it, and you wish to keep yourself open to such executive positions some day, than don't do it.  Walk, talk and maintain yourself in such a way you can fit into better paying jobs.  Because if you don't, there will be someone else of your same color, race, gender, ethnicity, skin condition who does.    Some might think these thoughts are racist - if I was racist, I'd keep that tidbit to myself to try to keep others from moving up.

text: I recently learned that the family of Dr. Shirley (played by Marshala Ali) is highly disappointed in this movie about their relative and how he was portrayed in this movie. They had Dr. Shirley portrayed as coming from a single mother but in reality his father was an Episcopal priest. He was not born into poverty but his family was actually middle class. He was never disassociated with other Black people. He was a child prodigy and a highly intellectual and intelligent man and fluent in about 8 languages. The movie would‚Äôve been 1,000 times better if they told the real story about Dr. Don Shirley but THEN they would‚Äôve had to market it as a Black film. That would be too much like right for Hollywood to portray any Black character in a positive light. Even showing the character through the eyes of the Viggo Mortensen character which is typical stereotyping of the Black man that he happened to drive for. Typical Hollywood foolishness.

text: In my humble opinion, Best Movie movie of the year. This film provided me with more entertainment than I expected. Loved the way the writer takes us into the lives, based on two "real-life" men. One an Italian American, circa 1960's, with little education, very biased, and who displays a very thug- like way of expressing himself. The other, a highly educated man, former child prodigy, who goes on to earn a doctorate in music.  Because of the racism that existed in the deep South, during that era, this talented pianist,  is barred from many southern, upscale hotels, and restaurants, because some folks found his skin color offensive. It was both heartwarming, and emotional, to watch how the author, slowly educates the wise guy from the Bronx to develop a deep sense of protection, love, respect and appreciation for the man who employed him as a valet and chauffeur.  And in turn, It was also very emotional to watch the deep pain and loneliness the musician silently endures. Throughout the film, I found myself wiping my eyes. The performances by both Viggo Mortensen, and Mahershara Ali, was nothing short of Brilliant. It would shock me deeply, if this movie, does not earn Oscars for best screenplay, best direction, best production, best actor, and best supporting actor. Highly recommend you seek this film out in your local theater.

text: My place didn't do it justice. It was showing two days ago in our mall's cinema but no previews in the screens, no posters, no promotion of any kind. You'd have to actually know about this movie and plan seeing it a day prior to actually know what it is. Great movie, not a masterpiece but this movie certainly deserved better than that kind of treatment. To think that they only played it twice in one day (3pm and 8pm) and made it share the same showroom as BUMBLEBEE that's been playing there for almost a month now in three other separate show rooms, showed how very little hope they had for this movie to make any money. Alita and Bumblebee took up the entire cinema with gigantic posters and trailer previews outside the mall and they can't even give the green book it's own projection room. Nobody else saw it but me. I planned on seeing it for months now but it took a while to get here so I was in time for the first screening. I've never experienced watching a movie in the cinema, literally all alone. I don't think they even expected anyone to see it cause when I went in, they turned on all the lights and the projector was out of focus. Good points for the projectionist though for getting it fixed, offing the lights and committing to his job. I enjoyed the movie a lot but it sure was a peculiar experience.

text: I'm a bit confused about exactly what the controversy is with this film. For me it was a really good movie with a great message and amazing acting performances. I would agree that it doesn't make sense for Mahershala Ali to be only nominated for supporting actor, when he is in the movie nearly as much as Viggo Mortensen. But the film makers have obviously done what people have done other years and nominated Ali in the supporting category because they think he will have more chance of winning  in that one. Other statements I've seen be talked about are that the movie has a white savour complex within it, and that it is unfair how Viggo Mortensen's character is the one that the story is centred around. The films gives a pretty detailed account of both characters, with the exception of their being more detail about the Tony characters family, but it is obvious that Mortensen's character would be considered the lead. But I didn't feel that this really diminished Ali's character in any way. I thought his character was well written and very interesting and complex. Probably quite a bit more so than Mortensen's character. As for the white saviour complex people are suggesting the film includes. I don't it's fair to keep referring to this every time a white character does something to help a non white character. It would be pretty ignorant for the movie to ignore the fact that a white character would be treated better and would be more privileged and to ignore how this might help a situation. And people seem to miss that in a lot of the films accused of including this, the white character progresses to being a better person or challenges the way they think because of the non white character(s). I'm not sure exactly how this makes the white character come off as a hero or how it doesn't show non white characters in a good light. If anything to me it shows how white society has been in the past, and still can be pretty toxic and promote bad ideals in people. Mortensen's character uses his street smarts to help Ali's character. And I don't see anything wrong with that. He did what any bodyguard would do, because essentially he was acting as a body guard amongst other things. And even if he weren't, I can't really see wanting to see why trying to help another person regardless of race is a bad thing. For me it was more that Ali's character just wasn't the physical fighter type and Mortensen's character was. I saw it as more that they helped each other out in different ways, because they both had different strengths. I feel like I'm being made to feel like my way of viewing this movie is from the ignorant and white perspective. But I don't quite see how the way I viewed it could be thought of as very ignorant. Unless I'm buying into the heartwarming feel good aspect of the films ending and that's a problem. And I just don't see why exactly people have chosen to criticise this film so much. I was hoping this would be a major contender for Best Picture but with people stirring up controversy about it, it seems pretty unlikely.

text: This movie really exposes the relationship between Africans and Italians in the United States. Both communities had a lot in common: Discrimination from the majority white population upon arrival from Europe. Italians didn't forget the derogatory terms like: Guinea and Wop to describe their ethnic origins nor did they forget the saga of Saco and Vinchetti. The role of Black musician in this movie clearly illustrates that both the dehumanization emasculation of Black men in this country was quite successful. The scene where their car got a flat in front of black slaves working in a field summed up the mentality of the average black person currently living in the United States: The male slaves who stood in the field staring at the black passenger and his white driver had the opportunity to jump over the fence separating and try to escape by asking for a ride, but instead chose to stand there and just look. That's the reality that Black people in America are currently living: They have the ability to leave this country and return home to Africa like their ancestors who returned to Liberia a century ago, but they choose to remain here and complain about the racist treatment they receive at the hands of White Spremacists.

Its all about big block buster and action packed tough guy crap, fast car and ego driven garbage. Psychotic thrillers that we strangely admire or special super soldier type killer like "bad assery",Followed by a few numbers to out do the next. But to make a movie which can cause slight controversy yet make you feel a certain compassion for another human being whoever they are. text: Initially, I had watched Green Book by accident. My friend and I had went to the cinema to watch Glass, but had misread the time it was shown and had missed the last screening. So, we started to look at what else was being shown, and came across Green Book. He wasn't really sure, but eventually we agreed and bought tickets for Green Book. Since then, Green Book has became both of our favourite films, and since then we have both watched Glass and thought it was... decent. I'm genuinely so grateful that we misread what time Glass was being shown, as otherwise we both would have probably never watched Green Book, and missed out on watching a masterpiece!
